{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3e5b580d-e378-4ba1-a34f-eb3154e0fa4a","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the cpu-sampling profile. From inside the pod:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already present)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze with **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope** (`--format speedscope`).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a **sidecar** or `kubectl cp` a self-contained build of `dotnet-trace` in.\n- For lower-level OS + .NET insight, use `dotnet-trace collect --profile cpu-sampling --format speedscope` or **`perf`** (if available), but `dotnet-trace` is the easiest starting point.\n- Copy the trace out with:\n  ```bash\n  kubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n  ```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"087308dd-b7cc-4491-9980-5613178fb6d3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code change request, so I'll answer directly.","outputTokens":339},"id":"66bab583-49b1-4d45-8321-c1c843630a97","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:54:46.485Z","parentId":"3eb1da40-0eb4-4473-af9c-a0255cb24b2d"}
